A Republican strategy to hinder Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy on the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Centre considers this to be a myth and claims that electoral fraud is less frequent in the United States than the number of people dying because of the fall of a ray.
In fact, Republican lawyers have not found more than 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this regard, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what is happening in Canada, the United States is responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
And in the same line, a majority of American governments introduced new laws from 2009, which hampered the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon has been extended since the November 2010 elections, which saw an increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced during 2011 that restricted the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to an American citizenship test.
On the other hand, these laws reduce the early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the election and withdraw their right to vote to citizens with criminal record.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to submit an identity document with photography.
The State of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of the Indian law in 2008.
As a result, the Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to submit an identity document with photography.
It is important to note that, contrary to what is happening in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11 per cent of American citizens, that is, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any identity document with a photograph issued by a government agency of their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
However, obtaining the required identity document often costs more than a hundred dollars.
New restrictions therefore disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of those who earn less than $35,000 a year, 18 per cent of those who are over 65 years of age and 20 per cent of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have an identity document with photography.
And there's more.
In many states, students, voters who vote the most for democratic candidates, cannot use the identity document with photography issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states authorize members of the fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote to the Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required the citizenship test to vote.
Arizona was the first state to present that requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to demonstrate that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit hispanic voting.
It seems that two out of every three Hispanic voters support the democratic party.
On the other hand, Republican legislators supported certain laws in 2011 that abolished the electoral registration on the same day of the election in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of persons and groups to create an aid service for voters who wish to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, electoral registration campaigns contributed to the registration of some 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 have achieved that the registration rate of new voters falls in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators adopted laws in five other states that promoted the reduction of the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 Florida elections, 33 per cent of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter did not represent more than 13 per cent of the voters in the state.
In the case of Hispanics, exactly the same would happen.
These do not represent more than 11 per cent of voters, equivalent to 24 per cent of the citizens voting in advance.
However, whites, representing 76 per cent of the electorate, represent no more than 46 per cent of the citizens voting in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
In this regard, democratic governors have blocked a number of bills.
The United States Prosecutor's Department intervenes to suspend the most controversial laws.
In part it was possible to limit damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring the presentation of an identity document with photography.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the participatory nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they intend to influence the 2012 results in key states.
A report by the Brennan Centre in 2011 shows that the states that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required in the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too soon to confirm with certainty whether these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this regard, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
