But in any exchange, a central authority controls and deals with the changes.
With the bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously depositaries of books of accounting, verifiers, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually done between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically through a double key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoins changes are contained in the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key feature is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file sharing, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "couple" the new transaction and add a number before "couple" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular score (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is good.
The transaction is then indestructiblely linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any change would change the score.
If, in order to commit a fraud, one user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would accept only as valid one of the two transactions; the other would be orphaned, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge is 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in the power of calculation.
The life of the network already has its heights.
The websites that offer Bitcoin services have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in storage.
"The error used does not affect the same protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money-laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash has the same defect.
Weight actors like Wikipedia reject payments of this kind.
Others, like the WordPress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the book of accounting and showed that about 80% of bitcoins are not circulating.
In November the "magnificent beads" were launched.
"The $30,000 have been changed," says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who turns the bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, the author of a pedagogical book on that currency, believes a lot about the potential of this technology as well as about the network of transactions.
Your system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a mobile payment without contact, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are cheaper.
The carrier also manages its identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to put into business, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
Just provide you with an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", requires Pierre Noizat, who assures you that there are thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
"There will be a time to impose Bitcoin, but there could be a change in 2013," he predicts.
On the other hand, in its report the ECB intends to re-evaluate the various risks, which are considered high today, if this currency succeeds.
