A Constitution with strengths in Egypt
It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever with regard to the constitutional declaration, which provisionally gives it full powers, he decided to play everything.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given that Assembly two months more to finish his work.
And nearly two years ago, Egypt used a provisional text, several times modified, which undermines institutional stability and leads to judicial error.
This new initiative has only increased fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president persevered in his "autocratic delirium" and continued "traiting his word" and "putting the right".
On the part of its supporters, it is ensured that this is a measure to end the institutional and political crisis more quickly and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time forcing the Brothers to give up their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, this is also a way of restoring popular and democratic legitimacy while the debate causes damage throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote for him, as he said in an interview with the American Weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "or I vote my text or keep the full powers", powers which are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist in their vast majority, voted yesterday.
Most of the liberals didn't turn to the summons.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not make their views worth.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, alternate members, were added yesterday morning at all speeds.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim brothers.
As I expected, the articles voted unanimously.
The commentators are grateful, on the other hand, that one of the few disagreements of the day has been expressed almost at the time of prayer, so that a number of committee members have come to think that the constitutional clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2 is the subject of all views, and is finally identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulates that "the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "standards", which would have allowed a more stringent application.
For Islamists, that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their good will and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
The liberals touch it with hypocrisy and consider it nothing more than a advertising craft.
According to them, Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its compliance with Sharia's laws.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we see the preeminences of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are also compounded by the fact that the next principal of the university would be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no specific religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have been working on this text are not academics, some of them formed in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he recognizes that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, since the terms used imitate the religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that could be raised in the future would be to what extent civil judges are competent to pronounce themselves over all this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms concerning the extended powers it gives to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers will claim that they are few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflict: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the revision of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament but to a national defence council.
Civilian proceedings in military courts, as requested by human rights associations, will not be prohibited.
They also showed concern about the text, which they considered to be libertarian.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially those of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, underscoring Heba Morayef, of the Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive was the prohibition of torture in accordance with Article 36.
The word was not contained in the previous Constitution.
