Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of European Space Agency Ministers last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of the ESA. It is the second member of the ESA of the former Eastern Europe bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began to work closely with ESA in 1994 and participated in the Agency's project commission over the years.
However, Poland’s journey to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already devoted to flying to space before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I recall, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at Warsaw's astronomical observatory in which, on 6 December 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneer study "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the indifferent assistants and, years later, Šternfeld remembered that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch award in France for his "Introduction to cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a major driving force for astronomy and cosmonautism.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known worldwide and his contribution to science was rewarded when his name was placed on one of the hidden faces of the moon.
Already in 1925 a train was built in Poland that was to be provided with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and the project's findings are not known either.
It is not clear whether the rocket would be used for the start of the train or for its braking.
Information on this dress is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
Starting in 1933, the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to the missiles.
The research was funded by the Komórka Techniki Armaenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawe Wolfkem and Prof. Gustave Mokrzyckiegim.
On the basis of the preserved material, it is evident that the investigation has reached the stage of the practical tests.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photo-electric hunting missile designed by the engineer Rohozinski appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpeda poietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile projects for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Association of Astronautiques (Polskie Towarzystó Astronautique).
The November 1954 issue of the magazine Problemy first refers to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronauts.
In one of them, by Prof. Mr. Subotowicze, it was proposed to create a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
From the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautic Society (PTA) aspired to form part of the International Astronautic Federation (founded in 1951) and in the fall of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the Vice-President of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He performed this duty until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM probe rocket (Meteorological Rocket), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and was first launched on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had an apex of 1,800 metres, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg of weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and two-stage RM-2 rockets started in the Błędów desert in the summer of 1959.
The rocket averaged 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket would be the object of a real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket would have an apex of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the wind of altitude.
However, the work was suspended in 1962.
The successor of the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from the available space for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for volume was 0.4 litres, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first air test started in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km high.
Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were subsequently built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into the COSPAR (Commission for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the National Committee of COSPAR two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined the space exploration of Soviet artificial satellites and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
